

# ==== Prefixes ====
# ✨ feat:     [sparkles]            Introduce new features.
# 🐛 fix:      [bug]                 Fix a bug.
# 🚑 fix:      [ambulance]           Critical hotfix.
# 🔒 fix:      [lock]                Fix security issues.
# ✏️  fix:      [pencil2]             Fix typos.
# ♻️  refactor: [recycle]             Refactor code.
# 🚚 refactor: [truck]               Move or rename resources (e.g.: files, paths, routes).
# 🔥 refactor: [fire]                Remove code or files.
# 🎨 style:    [art]                 Improve structure / format of the code.
# 🚨 style:    [rotating_light]      Fix compiler / linter warnings.
# ⚡️ perf:     [zap]                 Improve performance.
# ✅ test:     [white_check_mark]    Add, update, or pass tests.
# 📝 docs:     [memo]                Add or update documentation.
# 💡 docs:     [bulb]                Add or update comments in source code.
# 💚 ci:       [green_heart]         Fix CI Build.
# 👷 ci:       [construction_worker] Add or update CI build system.
# 🎉 chore:    [tada]                Begin a project.
# 🔖 chore:    [bookmark]            Release / Version tags.
# 🚀 chore:    [rocket]              Deploy stuff.
# 🔧 chore:    [wrench]              Add or update configuration files.
# 🔨 chore:    [hammer]              Add or update development scripts.
# ➕ chore:    [heavy_plus_sign]     Add a dependency.
# ➖ chore:    [heavy_minus_sign]    Remove a dependency.
# ⬆️  chore:    [arrow_up]            Upgrade dependencies.
# ⬇️  chore:    [arrow_down]          Downgrade dependencies.
#
# NOTE: refs. Gitmoji (https://gitmoji.dev/)
# NOTE: refs. Conventional Commits (https://www.conventionalcommits.org/)

# ==== The Seven Rules ====
# 1. Separate subject from body with a blank line
# 2. Limit the subject line to 50 characters
# 3. Capitalize the subject line
# 4. Do not end the subject line with a period
# 5. Use the imperative mood in the subject line
# 6. Wrap the body at 72 characters
# 7. Use the body to explain what and why vs. how
#
# NOTE: refs. How to Write a Git Commit Message (http://chris.beams.io/posts/git-commit/)
